@NODE Introduction "Introduction"
@{u}Introduction@{uu}

ParaKey is a code generator for use with @{"FBB" LINK FBB} @{"packet-radio" LINK Packet} Mailboxes. Most of these mailboxes nowadays require a personal accescode to prevent abuse of your @{"call" LINK call}.

When you access the @{"mailbox" LINK Mailbox} it will generate a 5-digit @{"code" LINK code} which corresponds to 5 characters in your personal @{"codeword" LINK code}. Looking for the right characters is a hard task. This is were ParaKey comes into the spotlight. ParaKey will generate the code for you.

There are already a few @{"FBB" LINK FBB}-code generator for the PC and there is also one available for the Amiga, AMIPASS. But the big disadvantage of AMIPASS is that it can only be used for one codeword. So you need to change the file to use it on an other mailbox.

ParaKey was started because I wanted to solve this problem and learn some C-programming on the Amiga.

The name ParaKey stands for @{u}Pa@{uu}cket @{u}Ra@{uu}dio @{u}Key@{uu}.

I finally released the 1.00 version after seeing something similar by Akari0. This piece of software is in Italian only and seems harder to use.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Legal "Legal stuff"
@{u}Legal stuff@{uu}

Though parakey has been tested in quite a long period, I am not responsible for any harm done to your computer.

Parakey is freeware. So you are allowed to copy it freely and modify the source in any way. PD companies are allowed and encouraged to include this program in their collection. The charge should only cover the costs.

The following files where included in the original archive:
@{i}Parakey@{ui}		The executable
@{i}Parakey.Guide@{ui}	The guide
@{i}Parakey.C@{ui}	The source in ANSI-C
@ENDNODE

@NODE Systemrequirements "System Requirements"
@{u}System requirements@{uu}

ParaKey will hopefully work with any Amiga.

It will only be of good use if you have got a @{"packet radio" LINK packet} node and a @{"FBB" LINK FBB} @{"mailbox" LINK mailbox} in your area.

ParaKey has been developed and tested on:

Amiga 4000/030
OS 3.1, 6 Mb, 170 Mb HD
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "Installation"
@{u}Installation@{uu}

Because the program does not consist of many files I have not made an Installer script for installation. Just copy the files to the required directory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE File "How to make a code-file"
@{u}How to make a code-file@{uu}

To make use of ParaKey you need to make a file which contains the codes for every @{"mailbox" LINK mailbox}. Just use your favourite editor and create a file called "ParaKey.code". This file has to be placed in the same directory as ParaKey.

Now you can enter all mailboxes and codes in the file. First the mailboxname and then the @{"codeword" LINK code}. The codeword is limited to 512 characters per mailbox. Enter every mailbox on a new line.

@{i}Example:@{ui}

EX0BBS THISISJUSTANEXAMPLEFORPARAKEY
PK1BOX ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ
CB0EGW EnrikoIsJustTypingSomeStuffForTheExampleAndThisLineCanBeVeryLong
@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "Usage"
@{u}Usage@{uu}

To get the code from ParaKey you need to start a CLI or Shell. You can then enter the parameters or just start ParaKey. If you do not include any parameters ParaKey will prompt you for the parameters.

@{i}Syntax:@{ui}
ParaKey @{i}<Mailbox> <5 digit code>@{ui}

where

@{i}<Mailbox>@{ui}      is the name of the mailbox you are connected to
@{i}<5 digit code>@{ui} is the 5 numbers that the mailbox generated after you typed SYS

ParaKey will then give you the code or key that you have to send to your mailbox. And that's it. The mailbox will now offer its services.

Hopefully ParaKey will be able to get the code numbers itself and enter the code or key in the @{"future" LINK future}.
@ENDNODE

