@NODE FBB "FBB"
@{u}FBB@{uu}

FBB is a @{"mailbox" LINK mailbox} program for the PC. On the CB-Band most mailboxes use this program. I guess it is also used a lot on other bands.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Packet "Packet Radio"
@{u}Packet Radio@{uu}

Packet Radio is communication between computers through radio waves. What you need is a computer with a special modem, BayCom or TNC, and a transceiver. The most common bands are CB (27 MC), 2 m. and 70 cm.

On the Amiga there are currently three programs available for PR-communication:
- AmiCom
- Amiga Host Packet
- JJanos

Currently a new program called Packet Wizard is being developed. Try an internet search-engine on it! 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Mailbox "Mailbox"
@{u}Mailbox@{uu}

A mailbox is a packet radio node which can store and forward mailmessages. A mailbox is what a BBS is to telephone communication.
@ENDNODE

@NODE code "Codeword"
@{u}Codeword@{uu}

For some @{"mailboxes" LINK mailbox} you need a codeword. Talk to the sysop of the mailbox to get yours.
@ENDNODE

@NODE call "Call"
@{u}Call@{uu}

A call is the name that you use on the radio wave. This name most of the time consists of 6 characters, of which one or more are numbers. It also often relates to your location (QTH).

For example: @{"My" LINK contact} call is CB0EGW. CB means I am a registered CB-Band packeteer in the Netherlands. The number 0 is just random and EGW stands for Enriko Groen, QTH: Wezep.
@ENDNODE
